      <body>
         <head type="date">
            <date when="1803-12-07">December 7, 1803</date>
         </head>
         <div type="entry" xml:id="lc.jrn.1803-12-07.01" n="lc.geo.1803-12-07.01">
            <sp who="wc">
               <speaker>Clark</speaker>
               <ab>
                  <date>December the 7th</date>
               </ab>
               <p>
A Dark rainey morning with hard wind at N, E, upon which point it blew all the last night accompanyd. with rain—    Set out a quarter past 7 oClock, the wing [wind] much against us    (1) passed a Small Island near the middle of the river; about 10 oClock the wind changed to the S, E, and gave us an oppertunity to Sailing    (2) passd an Island on the Starbd Side, at 12 oClock the wind was So violent as to take off one of the Mast's    (3) passed Small Village above the mouth of a large Creek,    This Village is Called <name type="place" key="Carondelet, Ill.">Viele Pauchr</name>
                  <ref target="n02120701" n="1"/> and Contains [<hi rend="italic">blank</hi>] families of French, Situated about 4 miles below <name type="place" key="Saint Louis, Mo.">St. Louis</name> on the Same Side, The high land continue to day on the Larbd. Side, I came to at 3 oClock at the <name type="place" key="Cahokia, Ill.">Kohokia</name> Landing,<ref target="n02120702" n="2"/> which is at the mouth of <name type="place" key="Cahokia Creek">Kohokia Creek</name> ¾ of a mile from the Town, and in view of <name type="place" key="Saint Louis, Mo.">St Louis</name> which is about 2 ½ miles distant.</p>
